<div id="review_1020041434" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1020041434" />
    <a title="Gustavo Vazquez" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8184722-gustavo-vazquez"><img alt="Gustavo Vazquez" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1568944655p2/8184722.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1020041434?book_show_action=true">Aug 07, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Gustavo Vazquez" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Gustavo Vazquez" href="/user/show/8184722-gustavo-vazquez">Gustavo Vazquez</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780061757754" href="/book/show/6291893-la-novia-oscura">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1020041434" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15876018711186108553">As I have enjoyed &quot;Delirio&quot; a lot, I&apos;ve got this book - the one Restrepo wrote before Delirio. But I was disappointed. The book deals with some whores in a city in Colombia, mainly about two of them, Todos los Santos and Sayonara, and it&apos;s written as if Restrepo was listening to an old Todos los Santos (and some other old people) remembering their &quot;adventures&quot;.<br/>I would like to compare with two other writers that told stories about whores. As a great accomplishment, I would cite the fantastic &quot;Mid</span>
  <span id="freeText15876018711186108553" style="display:none">As I have enjoyed "Delirio" a lot, I've got this book - the one Restrepo wrote before Delirio. But I was disappointed. The book deals with some whores in a city in Colombia, mainly about two of them, Todos los Santos and Sayonara, and it's written as if Restrepo was listening to an old Todos los Santos (and some other old people) remembering their "adventures".<br />I would like to compare with two other writers that told stories about whores. As a great accomplishment, I would cite the fantastic "Midaq Alley" from Naguib Mahfouz; it is real, captivating, credible, a work of a master storyteller. The stories from Jorge Amado are a notch below (about prostitutes, not the stories as a whole), with characters that seems to come from reality, but that receives some "strokes" that takes a bit (sometimes a lot) of reality off them, but makes the story flows better/faster/more direct, many times to it's own detriment. <br />La Novie Oscura is many notches below - completely unbelievable, unrealistic, not credible, even tough we have 400 pages of that. Restrepo probably really spoke with prostitutes as a jornalist, but the story is so light-hearted, even optmistic, commiserable, it tries so hard to be uplifting at the same time avoiding the "heart of the matter", that it seems completely unreal. The more you read, the more you forget Restrepo curriculum, and begin to believe everything was invented from the top of her head, as if everything she knows about prostitutes is by hearsaying. (There's a scene the whores put fire on a health clinic - just because one of them was verbally abused - that is just awful.)<br />In short, everything - every character, every event - sounds a bit shallow and the book as a whole is hollow.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15876018711186108553" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


